<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910320-0064</DOCNO><DOCID>910320-0064.</DOCID><HL>   National Asset Bank   Plans to Alter Status   To Expand Business</HL><DATE>03/20/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><CO>   NABK</CO><IN>REGIONAL BANKS (BAR)SOUTHERN U.S. BANKS (BAS)BANKS (BNK)TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)</IN><LP>   HOUSTON -- National Asset Bank, formed to liquidate souredloans made by the now-defunct Allied Bancshares Inc., saidits board approved a plan to reconstitute the company andallow it to start managing bad assets for others.   Under the plan, the bank would sell its remaining assetsto a new subsidiary called NAB Asset Corp., which then wouldbe the successor company. The common stock of NAB would bedistributed to current National Asset holders. NAB wouldcontinue to liquidate the assets, which at year end werevalued at $49.7 million.</LP><TEXT>   The new company would do other things not permitted underNational Asset Bank's charter, including managing assets forthird parties such as the government's Resolution TrustCorp., a spokesman said. The plan already has been approvedby the Office of the Comptroller of the Currency, but stillrequires approval by holders of 80% of common sharesoutstanding, the company said.   National Asset Bank shares, which initially weredistributed as part of the 1988 takeover of Allied by FirstInterstate Bancorp, were quoted 56.25 cents a share bid,68.75 cents asked, in over-the-counter trading yesterday.</TEXT></DOC>